Chandima,

Because abstract classes cannot be instantiated, you must use a subclass.

If you want to ensure that you are not testing code influenced by any
specific subclass implementation, then you could implement a
special-purpose subclass (for test-only use) and write your tests
against that subclass. The test-only subclass would need to implement
all abstract methods declared in your abstract class, but you could
ignore them for testing purposes (unless the abstract methods were
invoked by non-abstract methods on the abstract base class). Your
tests would exercise the exposed methods from the abstract superclass.

For illustration, let&#39;s assume that you have something like the
following (grossly oversimplified, of course ;-) :

public abstract class A {
	private int p;
	private int q;
	protected A(int p, int q) {
		this.p = p;
		this.q = q;
	}
	public int getP() {
		return p;
	}
	public int getQ() {
		return q;
	}
	public int sum() {
		return p + q;
	}
	public int foo() {
		return product() - sum();
	}
	public abstract int product();
}

You could then write a test case something like the following:

import junit.framework.TestCase;
public class ATest extends TestCase {
	private static final int P = 2;
	private static final int Q = 3;
	private static final int SUM = 5;
	private static final int PRODUCT = 100;
	private static final int FOO = 95;
	private static class MockA extends A {
		public MockA(int p, int q) {
			super(p, q);
		}
		@Override
		public int product() {
			return PRODUCT;
		}
	}
	private A aMock;
	protected void setUp() throws Exception {
		super.setUp();
		aMock = new MockA(P, Q);
	}
	protected void tearDown() throws Exception {
		aMock = null;
		super.tearDown();
	}
	public void testSum() {
		assertEquals(SUM, aMock.sum());
	}
	public void testFoo() {
		assertEquals(FOO, aMock.foo());
	}
	public void testProduct() {
		assertEquals(PRODUCT, aMock.product());
	}
}

The testProduct() method is superfluous, but I left it in as a
reminder that A#product must be implemented (because it is used by
A#foo). Note that the value returned by MockA#product is completely
arbitrary, but the value returned by MockA#foo must be correctly
computed relative to that arbitrary mock result. This allows you to
test A#foo without constructing a realistic implementation of
A#product, and without depending on any particular actual subclass
implementation of that method.

Hope this helps!

-jn-


